basics.label: DX Architect, Programmer, Geek, Father and Demoscener
basics.summary: I'm a software architect and code janitor from Oslo, Norway. I have a great passion for the web, programming, music, and most of all, my wonderful little family. I enjoy whisky and beer, perhaps while simultaneously producing music under my alter ego, Bitbear.

work.name: PayEx
highlights: Established Developer Experience as a business area, and assembled the team responsible for building and maintaining it.
Championed design thinking and user experience in the origanization, leading to Product & IT finally embracing it so much the different product departments are named Consumer and Merchant Experience.
work.summary: Senior Software Architect for Developer Experience, responsible for PayEx' and Swedbank Pay's developer strategy, developer communication, documentation, SDK's, modules, plugins, etc.

work.summary: Chief Technology Officer and former Principal Software Architect and Full-stack developer responsible for hosting environment, web standards and related technologies, the architecture of systems from design sketches through process diagrams to implementing usable web pages in HTML5, CSS3 and JavaScript, with back-ends and core domain logic in C#.

work.name: ErgoGroup

work.summary: I developed and architected software for program departments and worked for a large part in a EU project called ePerSpace, where I was a technical expert on web technologies and was responsible for the development of the information architecture of content creation and distribution.

publications.name: What's In A Model?
publications.summary: In this talk, I give ideas for how to structure applications in a way that will make you more proficient in your programming language all the while being able to more clearly represent and model the real world in code.

publications.name: What's Your Problem?
publications.summary: This talk will give you ideas of how to handle errors and exceptions that occur in your application, be it with the incoming request, database failures or errors received from a 3rd party, and how to serialize them into user friendly and actionable problem messages.

publications.name: Evolving compositional user interfaces
publications.summary: In this talk you are introduced to the evolution of compositional user interfaces and existing patterns while we discover their pros and cons, before diving into the architecture and development of compositional interfaces using hypermedia and micro-frontends. We go beyond the simple ‚ÄúHello World‚Äù example that always seems to work, and you‚Äôll learn patterns in modelling and design that will get you up and running with decoupled, composed user interfaces in your day job.

publications.name: Compositional UIs With Hosted Views And Hypermedia
publications.summary: In this talk, I demonstrate that by making your UI compositional through hosted views and by moving some of the business logic from the client to the server through the use of hypermedia, you can achieve full vertical integrations that are horizontally decoupled in a microservice fashion all the way from the persistence layer and up to the user interface.

publications.name: REST State Machine Revisited
publications.summary: This article addresses the discussions and questions posed  after the publication of ‚ÄúDesigning a True REST State Machine‚Äù and the talk it was based on.

publications.name: API Change Strategy
publications.summary: I describe a new approach to API versioning, outlining five aspects of smart API change management. Learn to adopt an API change strategy that avoids breaking change yet maintaining efficient development techniques.

publications.name: The REST And Then Some
publications.summary: This talk is for developers dabbling in REST, but who aren‚Äôt yet invited to Roy Fielding‚Äôs thanksgiving dinner. It will go through the history of REST and how it relates to SOAP and RPC-style APIs before delving down into the concepts of hypertext and hypermedia, how to implement them in your API and last, but not least; Why!

publications.name: HTML5
publications.summary: I was a member of the W3C HTML Working Group (representing NRK between 2002 and 2005) and Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group, contributing to the HTML specification and the development of what became HTML5.

publications.name: RFC 5023
publications.summary: I was a member of the IETF AtomPub Working Group, contributing to The Atom Publishing Protocol; an application-level protocol for publishing and editing Web resources.

publications.name: RFC 4287
publications.summary: I was a member of the IETF AtomPub Working Group, contributing to The Atom Syndication Format; an XML-based document format that describes lists of related information known as ‚Äúfeeds‚Äù used to syndicate web content such as weblogs and news headlines to web sites as well as directly to user agents.

projects.name: Web standards compliance
projects.description: I was an important force and resource behind the move from a highly table-based and inaccessible web site to one of the world's first accessible and cross-browser compatible media web sites with valid HTML, made possible with extensive use of semantic HTML, CSS and JavaScript implemented according to the W3C guidelines and recommendations WCAG 1.0, XHTML 1.0, CSS1, CSS2.1 and DOM1.
highlights: Ensured nrk.no was accessible had valid HTML

projects.name: Norwegian Tax Lists
